const summary = "'`Dataset ds001_breast was analyzed using the local dataset.parquet file only. The outcome was pfs_months, and all signed effects below are month differences from adjusted ordinary least-squares models unless otherwise stated. The main adjustment set included age_years, sex_female, postmenopausal, stage_iv, ecog_ps, brain and other metastatic-site indicators, node_positive, tumor_size_cm, ki67_pct, albumin_g_dl, ldh_u_l, weight_loss_pct_6mo, crp_mg_l, nlr, key breast cancer biomarkers, and treatment indicators.'"\\n\\nThe first adjusted main-effect pass identified a strong prognostic backbone. Higher age_years was associated with higher pfs_months ("'${fmt(mainFit.age_years.coef)} months per year, ${pf(mainFit.age_years.p)}). More advanced or clinically worse disease was associated with lower pfs_months: stage_iv ${fmt(mainFit.stage_iv.coef)} months (${pf(mainFit.stage_iv.p)}), ecog_ps ${fmt(mainFit.ecog_ps.coef)} months per point (${pf(mainFit.ecog_ps.p)}), and has_brain_mets ${fmt(mainFit.has_brain_mets.coef)} months (${pf(mainFit.has_brain_mets.p)}). Nutritional/inflammatory severity also mattered: albumin_g_dl was positive (${fmt(mainFit.albumin_g_dl.coef)} months per g/dL, ${pf(mainFit.albumin_g_dl.p)}), while weight_loss_pct_6mo was negative (${fmt(mainFit.weight_loss_pct_6mo.coef)} months per percentage point, ${pf(mainFit.weight_loss_pct_6mo.p)}).'"\\n\\nBiomarker main effects initially suggested that er_positive patients had higher PFS ("'${fmt(mainFit.er_positive.coef)} months, ${pf(mainFit.er_positive.p)}), while pik3ca_mutation (${fmt(mainFit.pik3ca_mutation.coef)} months, ${pf(mainFit.pik3ca_mutation.p)}), her2_positive (${fmt(mainFit.her2_positive.coef)} months, ${pf(mainFit.her2_positive.p)}), and higher ki67_pct (${fmt(mainFit.ki67_pct.coef)} months per percentage point, ${pf(mainFit.ki67_pct.p)}) were associated with lower PFS. These ER, PIK3CA, and Ki-67 findings were then refined through treatment interaction models, because the strongest signal in the cohort was treatment-predictive rather than purely prognostic.'"\\n\\nPalbociclib was the dominant treatment-associated pattern. In the adjusted main-effects model, treatment_palbociclib was associated with "'${fmt(mainFit.treatment_palbociclib.coef)} additional months of pfs_months (${pf(mainFit.treatment_palbociclib.p)}). Interaction testing showed that this benefit was concentrated in ER-positive disease: the treatment_palbociclib by er_positive interaction was ${fmt(jointPalbo.palbo_er_positive.coef)} months (${pf(jointPalbo.palbo_er_positive.p)}), and the ER-negative subgroup effect was essentially zero (${fmt(sub.palboErNeg.coef)} months, ${pf(sub.palboErNeg.p)}). PIK3CA mutation strongly attenuated palbociclib benefit: the treatment_palbociclib by pik3ca_mutation interaction was ${fmt(jointPalbo.palbo_pik3ca_mutation.coef)} months (${pf(jointPalbo.palbo_pik3ca_mutation.p)}). In ER-positive PIK3CA-wildtype patients, palbociclib was associated with ${fmt(sub.palboErPosPikWt.coef)} additional months (${pf(sub.palboErPosPikWt.p)}), while in ER-positive PIK3CA-mutated patients the effect was ${fmt(sub.palboErPosPikMut.coef)} months (${pf(sub.palboErPosPikMut.p)}).'"\\n\\nKi-67 further separated the palbociclib-responsive subgroup. The treatment_palbociclib by centered ki67_pct interaction was "'${fmt(jointPalbo.palbo_ki67_centered.coef)} months per Ki-67 percentage point (${pf(jointPalbo.palbo_ki67_centered.p)}), meaning higher proliferation reduced the palbociclib-associated PFS gain. The most favorable subgroup, er_positive with PIK3CA-wildtype and ki67_pct <= 25, had a ${fmt(sub.palboBest.coef)} month palbociclib association (${pf(sub.palboBest.p)}). In otherwise similar ER-positive PIK3CA-wildtype patients with ki67_pct > 25, the palbociclib coefficient was ${fmt(sub.palboHighKi.coef)} months (${pf(sub.palboHighKi.p)}). Stage IV status did not materially modify palbociclib effect; the palbociclib by stage_iv interaction was ${fmt(palboStage.coef)} months (${pf(palboStage.p)}).'"\\n\\nSeveral expected targeted-therapy biomarker interactions were not supported. The treatment_tamoxifen by er_positive interaction was "'${fmt(tamoxifenEr.coef)} months (${pf(tamoxifenEr.p)}). The treatment_trastuzumab by her2_positive interaction was ${fmt(trastuzumabHer2.coef)} months (${pf(trastuzumabHer2.p)}). The treatment_olaparib by BRCA1/2-any mutation interaction was ${fmt(olaparibBrca.coef)} months (${pf(olaparibBrca.p)}). The treatment_pembrolizumab by autoimmune_disease interaction was ${fmt(pembAuto.coef)} months (${pf(pembAuto.p)}), not the hypothesized lower effect in autoimmune disease. The treatment_sacituzumab_govitecan by her2_low interaction was ${fmt(saciHer2Low.coef)} months (${pf(saciHer2Low.p)}).'"\\n\\nOverall, the cohort shows strong clinical severity associations and a highly specific treatment-biomarker-outcome relationship for palbociclib: benefit is concentrated in er_positive, PIK3CA-wildtype, lower-Ki-67 patients, and disappears in ER-negative, PIK3CA-mutated, or high-Ki-67 subgroups. Other examined treatment-biomarker hypotheses were refuted or statistically unsupported in this dataset.\\n"'`;
